      <chapter id="1103">
        <pagenum>4</pagenum>
        <subchapter>0</subchapter>
        <title>What the research says about integrating basic academic skills</title>
        <content>&lt;p&gt;Contextualizing instruction is a key strategy teachers can use to integrate workforce preparation activities into academic instruction to help students make important connections between the world of work, their career goals, and their academic skill-building to fully prepare adults for success in college and careers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not only is it important for learners to apply their knowledge to different contexts, but numerous studies point to the importance of practicing and transferring academic skills to a variety of settings in order for &lt;a href="$@GLOSSARYVIEWBYID*6319@$&amp;amp;mode=entry&amp;amp;hook=306" target="_blank"&gt;deeper learning &lt;/a&gt;and retention to occur. Further, a feature in the development of expertise is the ability is to use knowledge flexibly and apply it across multiple tasks and situations. A key practice to promote deeper learning, then, is to teach with examples and cases that illustrate how a general concept can be applied to a variety of situations. The same goal is at the heart of what is typically referred to as “&lt;a href="$@GLOSSARYVIEWBYID*6319@$&amp;amp;mode=entry&amp;amp;hook=303"&gt;contextualized instruction&lt;/a&gt;” (Pellegrino et al., 2012; Lesgold &amp;amp; Welch-Ross, 2012, p. 108).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img width="550" height="367" alt="Photo of three women, studying in an adult education class" src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/45374571_m.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content>
