&lt;p&gt;WIOA defines digital literacy skills as skills “associated with using technology to enable users to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;find;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;evaluate;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;organize;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;create; and&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;communicate information&lt;i&gt;”&lt;/i&gt; (WIOA, 2014. Sec 463.3).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The U.S. Department of Education’s Office of Career, Technical, and Adult Education (OCTAE) &lt;span class="nolink"&gt;Employability Skills Framework&lt;/span&gt; provides additional details about using appropriate digital technologies for&lt;i&gt; “&lt;/i&gt;calculating, collecting and displaying data, conducting research, creating presentations, and writing reports.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img width="550" height="218" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" alt="Icons representing digital literacy skills including “find” (looking glass over a shape of a head), “evaluate” (scale)0, “organize” (schedule), “create” (lightbulb), and “communicate” (two talking bubbles, with one inside the other)." src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/icons_DigitalLiteracy.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #693300; font-family: Verdana; font-size: small;" size="2" face="Verdana" color="#693300"&gt;Click the arrow to continue on to &lt;a href="$@BOOKVIEWBYIDCH*6297*1109@$"&gt;What research says about digital literacy skills&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content>
