      <chapter id="1109">
        <pagenum>10</pagenum>
        <subchapter>0</subchapter>
        <title>What the research says about digital literacy skills</title>
        <content>&lt;p&gt;While the focus of digital literacy is on gathering and reporting on information, a broader definition of digital literacy includes “complex problem solving in technology-rich environments” (OECD, 2012). In this definition, digital literacy involves the ability to use a variety of technology tools to communicate, network, and perform everyday practical tasks for personal, work, and civic purposes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Current data, gathered through a 2012 large-scale study of adult skills, paint a picture of U.S. adults’ skills in tasks such as:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;purchasing items online;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;finding specific information; and&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;managing personal data such as finances (NCES, 2013).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The same study shows that U.S. adults generally have a lower proficiency to complete complex problem solving tasks in technology-rich environments than our international counterparts. This study highlights the case for increasing the emphasis on digital literacy skills at all levels of adult education.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These skills cut across multiple contexts and settings beyond the workplace. Digital literacy and technology used for communication and information-processing are critical to function effectively within home, community, social, and educational contexts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="graybox"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;More Information&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To learn more, explore federal &lt;a href="https://lincs.ed.gov/state-resources/federal-initiatives/digital-literacy"&gt;digital literacy resources&lt;/a&gt;, including materials for students, teachers and tutors, and program administrators.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="color: #993300;"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content>
