      <chapter id="1112">
        <pagenum>13</pagenum>
        <subchapter>0</subchapter>
        <title>What the research says about self-management skills</title>
        <content>&lt;p&gt;Studies have shown that providing people with the opportunity to articulate a desired outcome and develop an action plan that takes into consideration potential obstacles and their solutions is more effective in fostering goal attainment than simply articulating a goal without an accompanying plan (Shechtman, Yarnall, Stites, &amp;amp; Cheng, 2016).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The process of articulating goals, developing action plans, and celebrating progress made towards achieving the goal is a key to student persistence and further underscores the importance of self-management skills (Comings, Parrella, &amp;amp; Soricone, 1999).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/self-management.jpg" width="550" height="196" alt="Concept graphic showing a man drawing while other objects surround him, to convey self-management." /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="graybox"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;More Information&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p class="MoreInfoBox"&gt;Explore the TEAL Fact Sheets on &lt;a href="https://lincs.ed.gov/sites/default/files/3_TEAL_Self%20Reg%20Learning.pdf"&gt;Self-Regulated Learning&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://lincs.ed.gov/sites/default/files/10_TEAL_Self_Reg_Strat_Dev_0.pdf"&gt;Self-Regulated Strategy Development&lt;/a&gt; for more information and instructional strategies on how to help students learn, use, and adopt this approach.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;
