      <chapter id="1113">
        <pagenum>14</pagenum>
        <subchapter>0</subchapter>
        <title>Self-management and self-regulation used interchangeably</title>
        <content>&lt;p&gt;In the context of learning, the term &lt;i&gt;self-management&lt;/i&gt; is often used interchangeably with the term &lt;i&gt;self-regulation&lt;/i&gt;. Effective and persistent learners are found to employ metacognitive strategies and self-regulation skills, such as:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;asking questions;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;taking notes;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;analyzing the task at hand;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;setting learning goals;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;managing time on task; and&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;monitoring progress.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p class="MoreInfoBox"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/36972737_m.jpg" width="550" height="366" alt="A pair of hands writing on a notepad, with sticky notes and a tablet, on a wooden table." style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="MoreInfoBox" style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="graybox"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;More Info&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p class="MoreInfoBox"&gt;For more information on metacognition, strategies, and processes, explore the TEAL Fact Sheet on &lt;a href="https://lincs.ed.gov/sites/default/files/4_TEAL_Metacognitive.pdf"&gt;Metacognitive Processes&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</content>
